http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: 23 Dec 2011
Source: China Daily/Xinhua [edited]
http://www2.chinadaily.com.cn/xinhua/2011-12-23/content_4774852.html

Interview: Schmallenberg virus to be addressed properly: expert
-----------------------------------------------------
As a new virus was found infecting at least 4 livestock farms, and 33
livestock farms have reported suspicious cases on Friday [23 Dec
2011], experts warned that the Schmallenberg virus needs to be treated
properly.

"We don't know how big this outbreak will be. This is too early to
say. Fortunately the season of the midge, the insect that is most
likely to spread the virus, is almost over now," said Wim Van der
Poel, a researcher and virologist at the Central Veterinary Institute
(CVI) in the Netherlands.

He added that the specific virus, which caused birth defects by lambs
and calves such as hydrocephalus, stiff articulations, crooked necks
and even dead births, is a variety that was never seen before.

In order to map the extent of the virus, the Dutch Ministry of
Agriculture announced a notification obligation for farmers on
Wednesday.

"As soon as a [farm] reports a suspicious case, blood [samples] of the
mother animal and brain tissue of the lamb will go to the CVI. So far
we have researched around 30 cases," Van der Poel told Xinhua.

Van der Poel said in August and September this year, over 80 livestock
farmers in the Netherlands reported diarrhea, fever and a decrease of
milk yield of their livestock to the Healthcare for Animals (GD). But
the animals recovered while the cause of the disease was not found.

In November, the German Friedrich Loffler Institute took blood samples
of sick cattle in Germany and found a new virus that they called the
Schmallenberg virus, which was named after the place where the
outbreak occurred.

According to the CVI, further research needs to be done in order to
understand the history of the virus. It is shown that the virus shows
resemblances to the Akabanevirus, which is a well-known
disease-causing organism detected by ruminant animals in Asia and
Australia.

"We have never seen this variety of the virus before," Van der Poel
said.

The most important transmission route of the virus family to which the
Schmallenberg virus belongs is via vectors (midges). At this time of
year the vectors are no longer active.

According to the experts at the Dutch National Institute for Public
Health and the Environment, the information available indicates that
while transmission of the virus to humans cannot be excluded, it is
highly unlikely.

"No symptoms in humans have been detected, even during the months of
August and September 2011, which veterinary institutes show to have
been the peak incidence of infections in cattle," the Dutch Ministry
of Agriculture said in a press release.

Livestock farmer Gert van de Bor has 1000 sheep and a few calves. So
far there were no indications of malformed lambs or calves at his
farm. "But the sheep are about to give birth again, so we will have to
wait and see how that goes," Van de Bor told Xinhua.

