Communicated by:
H.J.Baker, DVM
Etobicoke, Ontario
e-mail <drhugh@sympatico.ca>



[It seems that the findings of the German, followed by the Dutch and
Belgian investigators, are indicative of SBV highly suspicious to be
the etiological agent behind the malformed animals (so far,
particularly sheep). The final proof might be expected, probably, from
experimental infection trials in pregnant animals.

Dr Baker's comment reminds the initial deliberations during the early
stages of the appearance, in northern Israel, of arthrogrypotic calves
(starting December 1969; hydranencephaly appeared in calves 2-4 months
later) and of AH (Arthrogryposis-hydranencephaly) lambs and kids
(starting January 1970). Several main lines of possible etiologies
were initially considered: toxic, environmental, genetic and
infectious. The long DD list of potential causes of the (hitherto
unknown) phenomenon included, inter alia, toxic plants, insecticides,
herbicides, radiation (thyroid glands collected in slaughterhouses and
tested), past vaccinations, genetics, and several infectious agents -
in particular Bluetongue, a virus known to (seasonally) circulate in
Israel.

The epidemiological investigations in sheep and goats led, in mid
1970, to the following conclusions:
1. The epizootic was caused by an infective agent, possibly
insect-borne, which was active in the northern part of Israel, mainly
in lower altitudes, during the months October - December 1969.
2. The agent caused abortions in sheep and goats.
3. The agent caused malformations, mainly hydranencephaly, in fetuses
between 30 - 50 days of gestation. No malformations were caused in
fetuses during the last 100 days of pregnancy.
4. Peak months of the syndrome were February-March. In badly affected
flocks, 50 percent of all lambs and kids were abnormal during these
months.
5. No clinical symptoms were seen in pregnant animals.
6. Males, twins and goats were more affected than females, singles and
sheep.
7. The vector could be similar to the one transmitting bluetongue.

The assumption that the pathological changes were due to an infective
agent, active during the autumn months, received support from the
finding of high levels of immunoglobulins in the pre-colostral sera of
calves and lambs; no elevation was seen in unaffected offspring. Tests
of these samples for bluetongue were, though, negative. The identity
of the pathogen remained obscure.

Following the later discovery, in Japan (1974) and Australia (1975),
that their respective major AH episodes had been caused by the Akabane
virus (kept in a Japanese collection since 1960), a retrospective
examination of pre-colostral sera from the 1969/1970 event, kept
frozen since, was carried out by the Kimron Veterinary Institute in
Israel (1975). It revealed antibodies to Akabane virus (antigen kindly
provided by the Japanese investigators). Sera, collected in 1975 from
cows older than 5 years from farms which had been affected in 1969/70
and from unaffected farms, revealed Akabane-seropositives only in the
cows from affected farms. - Mod. AS.



